      <header class="post-header">

        
        
          <h2 class="post-title" itemprop="name headline">Polluting the head section for the sake of adding 3rd party services</h2>
        

        <div class="post-meta">
          <span class="post-time">
            
              <span class="post-meta-item-icon">
                <i class="fa fa-calendar-o"></i>
              </span>
              
                <span class="post-meta-item-text">Posted on</span>
              
              <time title="Post created" itemprop="dateCreated datePublished" datetime="2013-04-04T15:09:47+08:00">
                2013-04-04
              </time>
            

            

            
          </span>

          

          
            
          

          
          

          

          

          

        </div>
      </header>
    

    
    
    
    <div class="post-body" itemprop="articleBody">

      
      

      
        <p><img src="/assets/images/posts/head-meta-tags.png" alt="Meta tags hell"><br>The head section of a page is becoming the place to include information for integrating your page with external services. Thus, if you want to include support for <a target="_blank" rel="noopener" href="http://developers.facebook.com/docs/opengraphprotocol/">Facebook’s Open Graph Protocol</a> or <a target="_blank" rel="noopener" href="https://dev.twitter.com/docs/cards">Twitter Cards</a>, you need to include some custom meta tags inside the head section. This also applies to iOS large app icons or Microsoft shortcut integration.</p>
<span id="more"></span>
<p>Have a look at a page such as <a target="_blank" rel="noopener" href="http://www.theverge.com/2013/4/3/4179236/the-facebook-phone-is-coming-and-its-already-in-your-pocket/">this news on The Verge</a> and view its source HTML code. Removing common meta tags such as content type, favicon, RSS or description, we have this:</p>
